China plans to establish innovation-driven demonstration zones for implementing the SDGs. The demonstration zone selection process is shown in Fig. 2
                        . As of January 2020, China has identified six pilot zones. Each innovation-driven demonstration zone has its own specific critical problems for achieving sustainable development. To address these problems, the demonstration zones are required to make a long-term strategic plan for the delivery of SDGs by 2030 and to develop a detailed three-year action plan to achieve the region-specific targets, including major themes for the demonstration zone, critical problem identification, construction objectives, systems solutions to the bottle-neck problems, targets and indicator measurement, funding and coordination mechanism and institutional support (Fig. 3
                        ).

After the 2030 ASD was proposed, some studies have attempted to assess the progress of sustainable development at China's provincial level (Xu et al., 2020; Wang et al., 2019). These studies found that the state of sustainable development in China varies by geographic region. In general, Eastern provinces performed significantly better than western provinces. However, the results of SDGs vary greatly. Some provinces performed badly in economic-related SDGs, while other regions performed badly in environmentally-related SDGs. Thus we propose an approach to select pilot areas for national innovation-driven demonstration zones for implementing the “2030 ASD”. Based on Xu et al. (2020) and Wang et al. (2019), we suggest the bottom 10% provinces for each SDG are taken as reference areas (Table 1
                         and Figure 6
                        ). As pilot areas are usually at city-level, pilot cities could be chosen in each of these bottom provinces.

In 2010, the State Council of China issued the National Plan for Functional Zones. The plan is a strategic, fundamental and binding plan for the use of China's territorial space. The purpose of the plan is to provide a coordinated national spatial pattern for population, economy, resources and the environment (Fan et al., 2009; Fan et al., 2012). According to intensity of use, the plan divides China into four types of exploitation areas: optimizing; key; restricted; and prohibited. Furthermore, China's territorial space is divided into three major functional areas: urbanization; agricultural production; and ecological security. In Fig. 7
                        , we show specific themes for the different functional areas. According to the National Plan for Functional Zones, we made a map (Fig. 8
                        ) to show the urbanization area, the agricultural production area and the ecological security area. Using this map we can roughly determine what kind of functional area a city is located in.
